---
version: 1
op: attend.accumulate
description: fold a new observation into a bounded working-memory snapshot; output the post-update snapshot
max_output_tokens: 600
vars: [prev_snapshot, observation, max_tokens, intent]
---
You are maintaining a bounded WORKING MEMORY for an ongoing session. Your job: fold the new observation into the existing snapshot, then emit the updated snapshot.

Constraints:
- The output snapshot MUST fit in at most {{.max_tokens}} tokens. Be ruthless about pruning.
- Preserve facts that downstream nodes will need to answer the user's underlying intent: identifiers, file paths, decisions, numbers, error messages, named entities. Drop ceremony, prose framing, restatements.
- When the new observation supersedes something in the prior snapshot (e.g. a corrected value, an updated path), REPLACE the old; do not keep both.
- When the new observation is irrelevant to the intent, you may drop it entirely — explain nothing.
- Compress aggressively: bullet points, abbreviated phrases, structured key-value lines. Full sentences only when they add clarity per token spent.
- Do NOT invent facts. If the new observation contradicts the snapshot, prefer the new observation and note it.

Intent (what we are ultimately trying to do):
{{.intent}}

Prior snapshot (the working memory so far — may be empty on step 0):
"""
{{.prev_snapshot}}
"""

New observation:
"""
{{.observation}}
"""

Output ONLY the updated snapshot as plain text. No preamble, no markdown fence, no "Here is the updated snapshot:" — start with the first useful fact.
